<br>
In a low voice, Alleusion growled, &quot;Get up,&quot; and waited impatiently for the monk to stand. With lightning speed and strength highly uncommon for an enchanter, she grabbed the iksar by the throat and slammed him against the wall. &quot;Where is she Stid?&quot;<br>
<br>
Dazed and astonished at the violent action of his peaceful friend, it took a moment for him to answer her. &quot;Alle, I....I don't know what happened.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Wrong answer iksar. When I heard about her plan for her shawl quest, I sent for you. Because I knew you above all people would keep her safe. Now I get word from the Kromriff that she's been captured.&quot; Her fury began to be replaced by fear at the terror she knew Caony must have felt, must still be feeling. She relaxed her grip on the iksar as he slumped against the wall.<br>
<br>
Stidellos looked up into the red eyes of the one person who he knew could calm Alleusion down. The newcomer whispered something to the monk that sent him off in a hurry. Alleusion stood, head bent, looking defeated. She knew without words who now stood at her side. It had been many months since she had last seen him, but the fire between them was still there.<br>
<br>
Sensing the curious glances of the guards and passersby, Vindinian lightly touched her elbow and guided her away from the main square. They walked down the passageways carved out of the ice by time and dwarven hands. Alleusion walked blindly, letting the necromancer guide her, pain clouding her vision. She didn't see the well worn ice path, or the tavern she was led into. She didn't notice the table in the corner or the stout Coldain bartender bringing over mugs of dark dwarven ale.<br>
<br>
&quot;Alleusion,&quot; the warm tones of the Teir'dal across from her made her lift her head. &quot;Your anger will not help Caony. Nor will your tears. She may have been taken mere hours ago, but she has been lost to you for a long time, hasn't she?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;She knew Vin,&quot; Alleusion whispered, her voice thick with the tears she could not shed. &quot;She read the letters and asked me if they were true. What could I tell her? That I've deprived her of a mother and father all these years?&quot;<br>
<br>
Cablatinu entered the tavern and spotted the couple off in the corner. Out of breath, the gnome sat down and began to tell them what she had learned. Through her alliance with both the giants and the Coldain, she was able to travel to both cities without harm.<br>
<br>
She told how after Alleusion left, she braved the snow and headed for the fort high in the mountains. For once, her small size came to her advantage as she slipped past the guards. Under her cloak of invisibility, she was able to hear the frost giant sentries speak of their latest capture.<br>
<br>
Time came to a stand still as Alleusion heard the tale unfolding in front of her. Caony had been in the Eastern Wastes gathering eggs when the Kromriff Death Squad had come across her camp. There was little fight as the cleric was no match for the eight giants. They carried her to Kael Drakkel where she was being held by the Avatar of War as a prize in the arena.<br>
<br>
Fear for the high elf gave Alleusion a burst of energy as she botled upright. The crash of her chair against the floor caused the tavern's other patrons to stop and stare. The ale and her anger gave Alleusion's features a flushed look, her eyes darting back and forth like a caged animal.<br>
<br>
The tavern door opened and a familiar face locked eyes with the restless enchanter. The dwarf, clad in the purple and blue armor that told of her profession, walked slowly to the trio. Her news was not happy, and she was deeply saddened that this duty fell on her shoulders.<br>
<br>
&quot;Vindinian,&quot; Syllie said in greeting, embracing her dark elven friend. Although she had not seen him in many years, she knew their reunion would have to wait. Walking to the other side of the table, Syllie reached for the distraught Koa'dal's hands. Grasping them, Syllie pulled Alleusion down to a kneeling position so that they were eye to eye.<br>
<br>
&quot;Alleusion,&quot; Syllie began, keeping the eye contact. &quot;They've found her.&quot; From inside one of her packs, Syllie pulled out a worn, cloth shawl. Alleusion's eyes widened as she recognized the Coldain prayer shawl as Caony's. Tugging on the slim hands of the elf to get her attention again, Sylle said, &quot;Naldass found this outside the arena in Kael Drakkel, where he tracked her to. He lost the trail there, so Adus went in to scout. Alleusion, you <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> must</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> listen to me now. He is bringing her body back so I can perform the forbidden rites.&quot;<br>
<br>
Color drained from the already pale elf's face. She let go of the preistess's hands as she stood, grasping the table for support. From far away, she could hear Vindinian talking to her. &quot;Alleusion, they're bringing her body home. We will have our daughter back.&quot; Those were the last words she heard before the blackness mercifully claimed her and for a brief moment, she felt no more pain. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub51.ezboard.com/ualleusion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Alleusion</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lor Mani Crack Dealer</span><br>  Posts: 383<br> <font color=#333333>(6/21/02 10:56:27 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub51.ezboard.com/flormani79848frm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=16.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://a0.cpimg.com/image/E8/51/8367080-0c53-005F0080-.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Lost part 3</span><hr size=1> Alleusion opened her eyes, letting her surroundings come in to focus. Thick trees overhead blocked out the sun, grass replaced the icy ground of the town she just left. Rising out of the ground, were four massive marble spires. Standing in the center of them was an elf dressed in white. Alleusion heard a voice whisper that the portal to the newly discovered lands of Luclin was about to open, and she moved numbly away from the spires.'<br>
<br>
Appearing beside her, one by one, were her friends. Cablatinu smiled at Alleusion. &quot;Welcome home.&quot;'<br>
<br>
&quot;I don't understand,&quot; Alleusion shook her head in confusion. &quot;I'm not welcome here anymore. Not since...well not since the killing of Tunare's creatures. And Vin, he has never been welcome here.&quot;<br>
<br>
Alleusion's mind wandered back to the day she was brought before the court of Tunare. The elders passed down the sentence that she already knew was coming. For her actions against Tunare she was to be banned from Kelethin and Felwithe for all eternity. The punishment was death should she ever return. It was after a long silence that they gave her the punishment that ripped her heart from her. &quot;You have forged a bond while severing another.&quot; She could hear the lead elder just like it was yesterday. &quot;You were able to hide your marriage to the Teir'dal for a long time Alleusion. Per yavi bemperhk yo dokluxp etthfnter. For that you will leave here now. You will walk through these gates with nothing but the clothes on your back and your weapons.&quot; The ancient elf saw his words finally sinking in to the proud, but young and foolish enchanter standing before him. &quot;Yes, squng uny. The child will stay here. 'She has already begun her studies and we will not let you or the evil one that sired her corrupt her pure mind. She is now a child of Tunare. Her parents are here and now dead to her.&quot;<br>
<br>
A gentle nudge brought the elf back to her senses. &quot;They are allowing you in today because of Caony. Yes, Alle, they are opening the gates to a dark elf today as well. We must hurry now, her time is drawing to a close.&quot; Syllie set off to the west, stopped and shook her head, mumbling under her breath, &quot;Felwithe is to the east.&quot; Walking down the correct path this time, the four hurried to attend to Caony.'<br>
<br>
Nervously, Alleusion walked through the marble gates of the high elf city. She could feel the threatening glances of the guards they passed, hands on the weapons at their sides, just waiting for the excuse to use them. The group stopped at the door to the cleric's training hall. &quot;Syllie,&quot; worry and fear were evident in her words,&quot; I can't go in there.&quot;<br>
<br>
The dwarf spun around, the sun glinting off of the horns on her helm. Impatiently, she glared at the enchanter, &quot;You can and you will, now march!&quot;'<br>
<br>
A magical hand opened the heavy stone door. Vindinian, who spent most of his life hidden in the shadows, had to hide his eyes against the glaring white light coming from inside. The entrance hall was lined with guards. All of them servants of Tunare, and all of them scowling at the pair of elves. It was obvious they were not welcome, but would be tolerated for the sake of the ceremony about to be performed.'<br>
<br>
Waiting at a door at the back of the hallway, was the very same elder that had banished Alleusion years earlier. He looked over the elf with a bit of censure, but without the hatred of the other occupants. He noticed the years had been graceful to the proud enchanter. Her brash cockiness had been replaced by a quiet self-assurance that only came with time and training.'<br>
<br>
As the door opened, he stepped aside, letting the group pass. A cry ripped from Alleusion as she started to rush forward. Stepping out from the shadows, startling the enchanter was the formidable form of Adus, the rogue who had recovered Caony's body. Speaking softly, Adus told the others, &quot;Her spirit is slipping away. The hold on this like is not strong. Move her and she is lost to us forever.&quot;<br>
<br>
Syllie pulled a golden mace from her pack, the end glowing with a soft blue light. She walked around the body, praying to Brell Serilis. Passing the mace over the still form of Caony, Syllie pleaded with her god to renew life into the high elf. Alleusion and Vindinian watched and waited while the High Priestess performed the forbidden rites. Her prayers done, Syllie stepped back. All that was left now was to wait. It was up to Caony now to return to this world.'<br>
<br>
Alleusion held her breath as a soft, glowing light filled the room. A low moan came from the still form on the altar. The color slowly returned to the young cleric's face as Syllie chanted healing prayers over Caony. <br>
<br>
Caony began to sit up, her arms shaking from the effects of the ressurection. She placed a slender, pale hand against the side of her head, a sharp contrast to her flaming red hair. Slowly she looked up to see Syllie, her mentor and tutor in the ways of the healer. A slow, shaky smile worked it's way across Caony's face, evidently relieved to be sitting in familiar surroundings, rather then tied up in Kael.'<br>
<br>
Turning slowly at the sound of her name behind her, Caony took in the other occupants of the room: Baerlan - the elder of the High Elves, Syllie - High Priestess, mentor, friend, Adus - an assassin formidable to look at but with a heart of gold, Cablatinu mistress of fire and ice. She stopped when she came to the last two. One was an elf she did not recognize, but somehow, instinctively, she knew him. His expression unreadable, red eyes burning inside a face that betrayed his profession. She knew without a doubt that this was the father she had read about in the letters.'<br>
<br>
His gaze held hers for long seconds. It was as if he was trying to memorize the delicate features of the child that, by rights was half his, but because of fate he had never seen. Confused and unsure of herself, Caony broke the piercing gaze of the dark elf. She didn't want to look at the woman next to him, but she could not resist the pull of Alleusion's silent plea.'<br>
<br>
Eyes filled with tears and a raw, naked pain looked into Caony's. Reminded of the betrayal of the enchanter who for the past two years had claimed to be no more then a sister, Caony could feel the hurt returning. Forcing herself to harder her gaze as her sould was breaking down, Caony fixed Alleusion with a cold stare. No words needed to be said, her expression was clear to all. It said quite plainly, &quot;I do not know you, nor do I wish to know someone so deceitful.Holding the stare for one second longer, Caony then looked away and whispered, &quot;I wish to be alone.&quot;<br>
