<br>
     She thought back to her first memory of Alleusion. She had been in the desert for most of the day, and was taking a short rest on the docks of an oasis. There had been many others wandering by that day, most were just resting before moving on, others were waiting for a boat, Alleusion was doing neither. She was waiting for a giant.<br>
<br>
     Caony had been struggling with her meditations when she felt a soft breeze float past her. She blinked her eyes and looked up. It was as if all her surroundings had disappeared and she was able to focus all her thoughts into the spells she was trying to learn. Caony heard a soft thud in front of her and shook her head to bring herself back to the present. The face she suddenly found herself looking into could very well have been her own. The features were almost identical, except the elf in front of her was a bit older.<br>
<br>
     She introduced herself as Alleusion, a Beguiler in her 55th level of learning. Alleusion told of the quest she had been given, and the spoon she was supposed to get from the giant named Cazel. &quot;.....and since I don't think he's going to kindly hand it over to me, I'm going to have to obtained it by other means. Namely, I'm going to have to kill him,&quot; Alleusion said with a wry grin. All this had been said without Caony introducing herself. It was as if Alleusion knew who she was.<br>
<br>
     &quot;Of course I know who you are.&quot; Caony was startled, she didn't think she had said that out loud. &quot;You are the child I've searched for. There is no mistaking that you look like me.&quot;<br>
<br>
     Confusing thoughts and emotions raced through Caony's mind. Haltingly, she asked, &quot;Am I...your child?&quot; Caony watched as she saw what looked like pain enter the elf's eyes.<br>
<br>
     Shaking her head sadly, she whispered, &quot;No, not my child, Tunare's child. You and I are sisters, nay more then sisters. &quot; Reaching out, Alleusion grasped the pale hands before her, &quot;Other then my husband, you are the only family I have left.&quot;. . . . .<br>
<br>
     So deep in her thoughts, Caony did not hear the elder elf walking up behind her. After sensing his presence, she did not glance up. Slowly rising to her feet, she looked into the piercing gaze of the ancient leader. With a slight tilt of his head, they began to walk.<br>
<br>
     In silence, the pair walked along the water's edge through Felwithe. Leaning heavily on his staff, the old wizard motioned toward a path cut into the side of the hill. Smiling, he reached his hand out to the young cleric, offering her assistance. Odd, Caony though, he looks as though a good strong wind will blow him over, and yet he's offering me his strength to climb the hill.<br>
<br>
     When they reached the top, Caony paused to catch her breath. Layed out before her was the city of Felwithe. Nestled deep into the mountains the peaceful city had been her home for as long as she could remember. &quot;Why...&quot; she began, but a look from Baerlan made her stop short.<br>
<br>
     &quot;Many years ago, a young and foolish elf stood before me,&quot; looking out across the city rooftops, Baerlan began his tale. &quot;She had committed serious crimes against Tunare. Although she was not alone in her actions, however, she was the only one who had once allied herself with the goddess. She stood before the elven council and all her transgressions were laid out for everyone to see. This elf had turned against her people in the Plane of Growth, but that was not all. In secret, she had married. A Tier`Dal, a defiler, a creature of the night. With their union, they produced a child. You were that child.&quot;<br>
<br>
     Caony started to speak, but a sharp look from the wizard made her close her mouth. &quot;For her actions in Tunare's realm, she was banished from Felwithe forever. For turning her back on her own people and forging a bond with the dark one, we took away her child. You had already begun to show tremendous power in the healing arts, and we did not want the Teir`Dal to corrupt you and further.&quot; Baerlan turned to face the astonished cleric, sadness and regret were heavy in his final words, &quot;So you see, Caony, it was I, not Alleusion that kept you apart. She did not abandon you. I had not been able to forsee that she would seek you out. We could not protect you forever. If we had known this would never have happened. When Alleusion told you that you were not her child, she told the truth. The day we cast her out, we declared you to be Tunare's child.&quot;<br>
<br>
     The silence after Baerlan had finished speaking was heavy. He reached a shaky hand deep into the pockets of his robe. Slowly and with much regret, he pulled out a roll of parchment. A faded ribbon held the roll together. His watery grey gaze met the confused stare of the cleric. Recognition lit her eyes and Baerlan could see that Caony knew what it was that he held in his hand.<br>
<br>
     &quot;My letters,&quot; she said somewhat startled to see them in his hands, &quot;where did you find them?&quot;<br>
<br>
     &quot;Well now, Caony, they aren't exactly your letters are they?&quot; He asked softly as he watched the bright blush stain the pretty elf's cheeks. &quot;When Syllie was overseeing your training, she was writing to Alleusion. That is how she knew where to find you. While we could take away her rights to raise you, her determination and spirit sought you out. She did what she could to be near you, without breaking the bonds placed on her by myself and the other elders.&quot; His voice dropped to a whisper as he placed the letters in Caony's hands. &quot;So you see child, she did not abandon you, she did everything in her power to be with you.&quot;<br>
<br>
     With those words the ancient wizard vanished. Caony sat down, high atop the ivy covered city of her birth, alone with her thoughts. Her mother had not left her after all. When Caony had found the letters two years earlier, she had been deeply hurt. Stidellos had sent a request for help with the giants and she accepted, knowing that the mission would be dangerous. While she had been gathering her things, Alleusion walked in to the home they had been sharing in Freeport.<br>
  <br>
     She confronted Alleusion with the letters and as she watched the unmistakable look of guilt cross teh enchanter's faces, Caony flew into a rage. She threw her things into her bags as she hurled accusations at her sister, nay, her mother. Looking back one last time, she tossed a letter of her own onto the bed, and with Alleusion begging her to stay so she could explain, Caony opened a portal and left.<br>
<br>
*****<br>
<br>
     Baerlan turned from the ancient scrolls he was copying as he heard the heavy marble door slide open. Standing in the doorway was the elf he had left on the hilltop three hours earlier. There was a new resolve in her eyes and she looked to have aged a bit in the few hours she was alone.<br>
<br>
     &quot;I want to find her,&quot; Caony said shakily. She took a deep breath and looked down at her hands. Hesitating a moment, she fixed her gaze on Baerlan. &quot;What she did was wrong. The crimes against Tunare I mean. And as for her love for one of Innoruk's own? Well, even I know that we can not help who our hearts chose for us.&quot; Silence fell as Caony finished her outburst. She lowered her head from the piercing gaze the old wizard had fixed her with. He slowly closed his book, braced both hands on either side of the heavy tome and stood.<br>
<br>
     &quot;For you, child, that would be most impossible. Alleusion was last seen entering the realm of Cazic-Thule himself. The Plane of Fear is very unforgiving. Only the most advanced have been known to leave the plane alive.&quot; The door opened behind Caony, and in walked a young apprentice, barely into his first level of learning. He handed Baerlan a letter then left as silently as he had entered.<br>
<br>
     A knowing look entered the eyes of the elder. &quot;Ah Caony, it is time. There is someone that would like to meet you.&quot;<br>
<br>
     Confused and a little worried, Caony took the letter and began to read.....<br>
<br>
